Inflation in Europe has jumped because of food
The accelerating inflation rate in the euro area is mainly due to the constant increase in food prices.
In November, prices in the 13 euro area countries rose above expectations, with annual inflation of 3.1% recorded in October after 2.6%, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian issuers, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not reduce the basic interest rate, with the reduction, together with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, leading to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep inflation rates below 2%, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must 'switch off' inflation so that it will not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation was a 15-year record of 3.3 percent; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has been upsetting due to rising food and energy prices.
Wheat prices have risen 88 percent over the year, and soybean prices have also reached their highest since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 there was a substantial increase in the payment of food oils and milk products.
The price of oil on the world market has risen 52 percent this year, and last month, a barrel of black gold was worth nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1% this year to 2.5% in 2008 but will already fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3% over the next three to four months, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
