In many places, disinfectants are being saved
This year, more than 1,000 cases of infection were reported in hospitals, primarily due to inappropriate antibiotic use.
Hospital hygiene conditions, overcrowding of beds, overload of staff to stop the infection are not helping, says the National Epidemiology Center's primary.
In many places, disinfectants are also being spared.
Recently, the trauma department at St. John's Hospital diagnosed an MRSA infection.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were discovered in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same area earlier this year.
The patient who was injured in a serious car accident was released home, but soon afterward he had to return with MRSA infection and one major operation was not yet possible due to the bacteria in his system.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, Primary Director of the National Epidemiological Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been safely registered in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
Nearly two thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by AS (e. g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are given in excess or inappropriately, a bacteria that responds well to antibiotics will develop into a bacterium that is highly resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Sepsis can cause serious hospital infections, such as morning infections or blood poisoning, especially in patients with weakened bodies, low body weight, or old age, if their immune systems are temporarily or permanently dysfunctional.
According to the chief medical officer of St. John's Hospital, MRSA is not a special infection, similar infections are common in hospitals.
"Infection should not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there", Tibor Nyulasi said, "where the presence of the disease is not investigated".
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the healthcare staff treat them in rubber gloves and masks and we have the antibiotics we need to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are first tested for MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample is not in fashion
The vast majority of MRSA-related hospital infections could be prevented, but the current rates and conditions in home hospitals are not conducive to preventing the emergence and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is characteristic in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should check patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, microbiological sampling in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund this investigation is also a factor.
Most cases are detected when a patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, the primary epidemiology center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
It is necessary to strive for targeted antibiotic therapy or microbiological testing to prevent drug resistance, but this is not always the case in hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in the primary or ambulatory treatment of patients, Karolina Böröcz said.
Save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence suggests that MRSA is most commonly transmitted to patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but serious deficiencies exist in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by both capillary infection and touch, but in home hospital conditions, it is not always possible to isolate infected patients.
On the contrary, rooms are often crowded, and beds are often very close to each other, although epidemiologically patients should be at least 1.5 metres apart.
As Karolina Böröcz pointed out, unfortunately, we also find that in hospitals in poor physical condition, disinfectants are being spared, nurses are few and patients are many, which increases the chances of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there is a demonstrable reduction in such infections or the further spread of the disease agent can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treating MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so it's being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has a programme to prevent or reduce MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, with the published data showing a declining trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) lists the prevention of multi-residential disease agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these agents as among its priorities.
