Bulgaria is the realm of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is staggering - the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to the once somewhat neglected Balkan country.
Where and who are buying the EU's ever-cheaper but fastest-growing market?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The most sought-after destination for Eastern European real estate is undoubtedly Bulgaria now, with its cheap skiing apartments and seaside houses.
The most popular of these are the Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitoša regions, Albena, Gold Sands, Sunshine Coast, the ancient cities of Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for properties around Kavarna and Balcik.
According to analysts at Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will also attract investors and more and more buyers will also shop around the slums of the cheap city of Rus.
The capital Sofia is also a promise of attractive opportunities, with commercial and office space promising the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of Europe's most attractive golf destinations, becoming a popular destination for travel in the next two seasons, alongside the summer and winter seasons.
Foreseeable investors are already buying at a large market, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, real estate buyers in Bulgaria are also trying to change their lives and lifestyle.
Most customers are from England, but there are also customers from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
There are also Maltese and Cypriot investors, and there are traditionally many Russian customers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
The foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
The newcomers buy either renovated properties worth 50 to 100 thousand euros or decayed old houses worth 5 to 15 thousand euros, which they then renovate.
They demand good accessibility and communication, and they are interested in being close to a big city, shopping malls and, as a rule, a local doctor.
The second category is the chat customers (Bulgaria was ranked among the top 10 German recreational destinations in December).
The third group consists of commercial investors who shop in the hope of a medium or long-term appreciation.
Real estate prices in the capital are continuous as demand grows stronger.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, but has grown by 21% a year over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices significantly outweighs wage growth.
