Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased risk to the country
The Hungarian Guard's activity, established with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of the Institute for Political Capital.
The company's 'risk warning' states that the biggest political risk in the Hungarian Guard's activities is that 'the intensification of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary could lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term.'
The main reason is that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy is likely to be aimed at provoking such action, adds the research institute.
He writes that one of the biggest negligence of Hungarian politicians can be explained by the fact that "public discussion of the Roma issue has been left by the representatives of the radical and extremist political groups who could build political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict".
This deepened the problem, preventing normal dialogue, strengthening extremists and increasing the likelihood of violent conflict, the institute said.
Moreover, the work of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, has "substantially undermined Hungary's image abroad, especially as regards its belief in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
The Institute recalls: part of the reorganisation of the Hungarian radical and far-right groups, which has been gaining increasing publicity and enthusiasm since autumn 2006, is the creation of several organisations in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which call themselves 'National Home Defence' associations.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly declaring the willingness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the event of natural disasters, attacks on the homeland, disruption of order), in addition to pointing to the inability of the police, the army, or the state", he adds.
He further notes that all this is done in a way that seeks to enclose various political efforts built on the resistance of society to politics and parties in civil dress.
The emphasis on citizenship and the form of the association in the case of such groups is therefore not only a means of avoiding legal constraints on judicial registration but also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor in terms of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited by several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, and the ultra-nationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries have been appealing to the establishment of the Hungarian Guard to excuse their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All this could affect the political stability of the region", he adds.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so the political risks to the region as a whole have increased.
The Hungarian National Guard is similar to the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The Bulgarian Guard was created in the wake of the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of Sofia's districts (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU used that to set up a guard with the goal of the organization being "national defense".
She said that in the past 17 years, Bulgaria has experienced "gypsy terror", but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, recalls Political Capital.
He adds that the initiative has sparked a heated debate among the Bulgarian public.
He further writes that the increased risk of ethnic clashes is signalled by announcements by some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will create their own guard in a sign of resistance.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that Hungarian Roma will respond to the threat in a similar way, by setting up their own national defence, as can be seen in the Risk Warning prepared by Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, Research Director of the Institute for Political Capital, said: "Risk analysis is one of the activities of the Institute.
As he said, they issue a risk analysis every year and if they find anything that could affect a change in risk, they inform the public, such as in this case by issuing a risk warning.
