Loaded memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored for 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were, up to that time, only accessible for 'humanitarian' purposes, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of the former victim or her legal guests.
Eleven archival governments - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open the archives to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all States is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Free access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow them to study "especially the movement of prisoners, the population of the camps, and the health of forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives, managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, opposed the disclosure of these names to the public because of the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the presumed homosexuality or mental disabilities of some victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants compiled by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labour civilians, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are handling tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents", said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at the Berlin Technische Universität, in 2006.
