Congress has approved the transposition of MiFID effective November 1
In parallel with parliamentary deliberations that ended today with a vote by Congress on novels included in the bill by the Senate, the government has held a public hearing on the regulations that develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities necessary for the effective functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the individual supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial services provider (ESIS), financial advisory company (AFI) that will connect to securities firms, securities brokerage firms and portfolio managers.
In addition, the number of systems for executing financial instruments transactions is expanded by joining regulated secondary markets with multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems to compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also obliges investment firms to disseminate information on the market on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and risk management and requires the reporting of all transactions carried out to facilitate surveillance by the CNMV.
During the Congressional Commerce Committee's deliberations, several amendments were made, among them the one that highlights the need to consider securitised claims as a 'complex' financial instrument given the high risk to the investor, as demonstrated by what happened in the US with high-risk subprime mortgages.
The transposition of the Directive was also used to legally specify the functions that bachelors in economics and business administration can hold 30 years after the Royal Decree of 1977 specifying the professional functions reserved for economists was adopted.
The Senate also ordered the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary who will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for different investment firms at the same time.
