Concerns over a new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
The price of natural gas is currently being disputed between Russia and Ukraine, which increases the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev warned that if Moscow raises gas prices to Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for gas it gets from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in the negotiations", said Anatoly Kinash, Ukraine's economy minister, to Reuters.
'The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit charges (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.'
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev led to a reduction in Gazprom's supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a sharp drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up sharply.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the European Union's supplies.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
