The NHS Chamber is expected to check foreign staff for qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK before they are employed.
Although the Scottish Health Commissions use Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, this agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report of the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the Commissions should be guided by the guidelines of the Criminal Records Bureau, which assists employers with audits in several countries.
"While we have found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out on a regular basis", the report said.
Mr Black said that the Scottish NHS was in many ways aligned with its own pre-employment checks policy, but added: "Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information on the number of foreign staff is available".
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS staff who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is not clear what further value these comments will bring", he said.
The Scottish Health Authority has reported that there are currently 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the President of the High Authority noted that these figures are likely to be higher also because the Commissions had trouble identifying residence permit staff.
The investigation also found that the established control procedures of NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely carried out.
They included passport checks, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the pre-employment control policy and guidelines for NHS foreign workers.
Health Minister Nicola Sturgeon said: "I wanted to finish this job immediately after the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport".
