The climate on Venus may be a glimpse into the future of the Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may have once been a pleasant place for life.
Data from the European orbiting station shows that the planet is even more similar to the Earth's twins than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
These two worlds are about the same size and orbit around similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus had conditions similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the frightening greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and lower rotational speeds have sent Venus on a completely different path of evolution.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by storms and hurricane-force winds.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which studied the planet for a year, offer a modest view of how the Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Physics Department at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to compile a scenario in which Venus began as well as Earth, perhaps with a habitable environment, billions of years ago".
