Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis affecting the U.S. credit card market?
When blood is in the water, the spinal fins naturally begin to move around excitedly.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is in a slump, predators have turned to the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer credit options were infected by subprime mortgages.
The signs of tension are clear.
Increasing number of default cases (with more than 30 days of payment delay) and cancelled accounts (accounts deemed irrevocable by the provider).
HSBC last month announced that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it's too early to panic.
The accounts written and the inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody's, the third quarter default rate of 3,89% was almost an entire percentage point below average.
The deterioration of the rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The 2005 amendment to the US Bankruptcy Code led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore increase regardless of whether the general conditions for lenders deteriorated.
The sector also has a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And trust in the securities of the secured credit cards is stable, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup predicts that emissions will increase by 25% over last year.
There are certainly direct ways to spread the infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when real estate loans run dry, consumers are more likely to borrow through credit cards.
However, credit card issuers are more concerned with cash flow than collateral values, so falling house prices may not necessarily change the credibility of lenders.
They may even be beneficial to lenders.
The incentive for consumers to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up the list of priorities to repay.
Card issuers can also respond to more volatile conditions faster and more flexibly than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of rapid price changes in the guaranteed items.
"We're not going to be able to just reevaluate all loans one fine morning", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
While the risk of a subprime mortgage explosion is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt cuts push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
