Venus is the Hell Twin of Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more like Earth than previously thought, and the European space probe Venus Express on Venus has recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and winds at the poles.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that there is a flash on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought evidence - it has picked up electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere, and lightning is flying from cloud to cloud at a height of about 35 miles [56 km], wrote Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
According to a well-known theory of the origin of primordial matter, lightning may have created life on Earth, and storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
"If life ever existed on Venus, it must have been long ago", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus, and the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach about 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the hell twin of Earth, but it's a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, began to evolve in a completely different way is a fundamental question of the Esa mission.
Since no spacecraft has been launched exclusively for the study of Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of the Venus Express spacecraft in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of this planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of the research, presented in several articles in the journal Nature, did not just highlight the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
