These aren't Warhol's boxes.
The person who combines the terms Sweden and wooden boxes is not thinking of Andy Warhol, but of Ike.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes made in Sweden today cast dark shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Most of his list of 94 Stockholm-type "Brillo boxes" are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo boxes" a few months ago, internal research at Moderna Museet in Stockholm came with a disappointing result; the six "Brillo boxes" donated to Moderna Museet in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other Stockholm-style "Brillo boxes" in circulation on the international art market.
The events that precede it are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York City in 1964, painting wooden boxes based on the red-brick design of Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
The exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 featured - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes, which were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
It wasn't artwork, it was their presentations, just exhibits.
Warhol apparently also authorized several wooden Brillo bodies in Sweden in 1968, but they are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses there now speak of 15 boxes that were then rightfully registered in art and auction history as authorized originals -- "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" labeled the Stockholm Type.
Some of them were auctioned for over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred pieces were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol left him.
In fact, 105 Hultén bodies were only produced in Malmö for the Petrograd exhibition in 1990.
By this time Warhol was three years old.
Lars Byström, senior curator of Moderna Museet, examined in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their tiles had been painted with base paint and polished, were painted with oil white brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, showed that the paint was applied by a painter's roll directly on the slate without the previous base coating - in addition, it was acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo box list", Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve was quoted as saying: "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies".
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would address these "major charges" raised in the case of soap boxes.
But the organization remains in unrelenting silence.
